The electronic band structure of semiconductors is pivotal to understand photocatalytic properties of materials. Electrons in the valence band are excited to the conduction band after the irradiation of light gaining a higher energy than the materialâs bandgap, and the excited electrons activate the hydrogen evolution reaction. The bandgap is an intrinsic value depending upon the composition, and it is a main factor to determine active photocatalytic ranges in wavelengths. Although the energy should be sufficiently provided by light, the visible range is a major target of light absorption due to the large fraction of over 40% in the sunlight spectrum on Earth. Therefore, the bandgap of around 2.4 eV is generally preferred among various semiconducting materials (


